The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                      QUICK TAKES
                    
	Paris: President Nicolas Sarkozy held a face-to-face meeting with Thierry Henry on Thursday after Les Bleus humiliating exit from the World Cup turned into a national issue the government has vowed to address. Sarkozy called on Wednesday for a wholesale review of French soccer after chairing a government meeting and sports minister Roselyne Bachelot said on Thursday the resignation of French Federation chairman, Jean-Pierre Escalettes was unavoidable.         
	Johannesburg: Want to hear what your favourite pop star or politician sounds like accompanied by the most memorable sound of the soccer World Cup in South Africa  the droning vuvuzela trumpet?    
	Try YouTube. The popular video-sharing website has added a vuvuzela button  in the form of a soccer ball  on its latest video player, allowing the sound of the vuvuzela to play alongside the video being watched.         
	Erasmia: Germany midfielder Bastian Schweinsteiger could miss the second-round World Cup match with England because of a right-thigh injury. Assistant coach Hansi Flick says time is short until Sundays match in Bloemfontein to get Schweinsteiger fit.         
	Johannesburg: France playmaker Franck Ribery will undergo groin surgery on Friday, a team spokesman said on Thursday. The player was to leave South Africa on a plane chartered by his Bayern Munich club and would be operated on in Munich, the spokesman added.         
	Athens: Greece have began their search for a new coach after Otto Rehhagels tenure came to an end following his teams World Cup exit. Rehhagels contract expires at the end of this month and his assistant Yiannis Topalidis, who announced his departure after the 0-2 loss to Argentina, has confirmed that the 71-year-old German has bid farewell to his players.         
	Johannesburg: South Africa plans to have a million flags flying next week to maintain the momentum of the World Cup despite the host nation being bundled out of the tournament. A One Million Flags March is planned for July 3, a spokesman said.                                                                                                                                                         
